summaries.title: Balancing Pressure, Pride, and Belonging
summaries.summaryText: Daniel expressed pride in representing his familys aspirations but also noted ongoing struggles with imposter syndrome. He values belonging through peer groups that normalize his experiences as a first-gen student of color in STEM. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Representation and Visibility in Engineering Spaces
summaries.summaryText: She emphasized how few Black women were visible in faculty and leadership roles, describing representation as both motivating and emotionally taxing. Her NSBE involvement offered vital affirmation and a platform to advocate for equity. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Developing Academic Confidence Through Mentorship
summaries.summaryText: Daniel described feeling initially out of place in rigorous electrical engineering courses, particularly when comparing himself to peers with prior robotics or coding experience. His confidence improved after joining a peer mentoring program where upperclassmen provided guidance and reassurance. [Part 4/4]

summaries.title: Integrating Mental Health Advocacy with STEM Identity
summaries.summaryText: Sarah described bridging mental health awareness into STEM culture through peer-led workshops. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Transition from High School to University-Level Engineering
summaries.summaryText: Luis found the shift from project-based high school learning to theory-heavy coursework challenging but rewarding. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Building Inclusive Engineering Teams
summaries.summaryText: Ethan noted that successful project outcomes often came from teams with diverse backgrounds and perspectives. He believes empathy and active listening should be core engineering competencies. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Balancing Academic Rigor with Limited Peer Representation
summaries.summaryText: Maria described feeling academically capable but often isolated in her computer engineering courses, where few other Latina students were enrolled. She mentioned that faculty were supportive when approached, but that representation and group belonging remained low, especially during first-year lab sections. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Leadership and Mentorship in Engineering Design Projects
summaries.summaryText: Aaliyah described how leading senior design teams strengthened her confidence in project management and technical problem-solving. She reflected on mentorship as a core component of her academic identity, often supporting younger women of color navigating engineering culture. [Part 4/4]

themes.title: Emotional Labor and Advocacy Burden in Underrepresented Students
themes.description: Aaliyahs experience illustrates how women of color in engineering often balance advocacy roles with academic demands, leading to invisible emotional labor that institutions rarely acknowledge. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Normalizing Mental Health Conversations in STEM
themes.description: Sarahs work highlights the growing student-led shift toward wellness advocacy within rigorous majors. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Sense of Belonging in STEM for Students of Color
themes.description: Marias reflections highlight how peer representation and visibility in classrooms significantly influence belonging and persistence for Latina women in engineering. [Extended 4]

themes.title: Navigating Institutional Barriers as a First-Generation Student
themes.description: First-generation identity shapes how Maria interprets bureaucratic and academic systems, creating additional cognitive and emotional labor compared to continuing-generation peers. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Acknowledging Structural Advantage and Allyship in STEM
themes.description: Ethans reflections underscore the role of allyship among students who recognize their positional privilege. He highlights how acknowledging systemic inequities can lead to more equitable classroom dynamics. [Extended 4]

themes.title: Peer Mentorship as a Belonging Intervention
themes.description: Daniel emphasized how structured mentorship programs provided psychological safety and belonging cues, normalizing struggle and improving persistence among marginalized students. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Normalizing Mental Health Conversations in STEM
themes.description: Sarahs work highlights the growing student-led shift toward wellness advocacy within rigorous majors. [Extended 2]

themes.title: Family Expectations and Cultural Motivation
themes.description: Cultural values around family honor and sacrifice serve both as motivation and a source of pressure for first-generation Vietnamese-American students pursuing STEM. [Extended 3]

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Visibility of First-Gen Student Resources
areasForImprovement.description: Current communication about financial aid, academic advising, and mentorship resources does not adequately reach first-generation students. Improving targeted outreach through orientation and department emails could reduce inequities in access to support. [Extended 4]
actionItems: Add first-gen resource links to department portals

areasForImprovement.title: Normalize Academic Struggle Through Faculty Messaging
areasForImprovement.description: Faculty can help counter imposter syndrome by sharing personal learning experiences, highlighting that mastery develops over time and through mistakes. [Extended 1]
actionItems: Encourage faculty to include learning journeys in course introductions
Develop short workshops on inclusive teaching practices

areasForImprovement.title: Enhance First-Gen Orientation Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Provide stronger academic transition support for first-generation students entering engineering. [Extended 4]

areasForImprovement.title: Integrate Wellness Programming into STEM Curriculum
areasForImprovement.description: Develop optional workshops or credit modules linking mental health and STEM performance. [Extended 3]
